onth","3 months","6 months","12 months","2 years"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBy \u003Cstrong\u003E3 months\u003C/strong\u003E of age, infants develop the ability to voluntarily open and close their hands and track moving objects with their eyes. These are important developmental milestones that indicate normal neurological maturation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt \u003Cstrong\u003E1 month\u003C/strong\u003E, infants typically have a grasp reflex and can focus on objects 20-30 cm away but cannot yet track moving objects smoothly or control hand movements voluntarily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy \u003Cstrong\u003E6 months\u003C/strong\u003E, infants have progressed beyond these basic skills and can transfer objects between hands and reach for objects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy \u003Cstrong\u003E12 months\u003C/strong\u003E, fine motor skills have developed further to include pincer grasp.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy \u003Cstrong\u003E2 years\u003C/strong\u003E, children have much more advanced fine motor skills including scribbling and building towers with blocks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["By 3 months of age, infants can open and close their hands voluntarily and track moving objects with their eyes.","Visual tracking and voluntary hand movements are important developmental milestones that indicate normal neurological development."],"references":["Dosman CF, Andrews D, Goulden KJ. Evidence-based milestone ages as a framework for developmental surveillance. Paediatr Child Health. 2012 Dec;17(10):561-8. doi: 10.1093/pch/17.10.561. PMID: 24294064; PMCID: PMC3549694.","Flensborg-Madsen, T., Gr\u00f8nkj\u00e6r, M. \u0026 Mortensen, E.L. Predictors of early life milestones: Results from the Copenhagen Perinatal Cohort. BMC Pediatr 19, 420 (2019). https://doi.org/10.1186/s12887-019-1778-y","Misirliyan SS, Boehning AP, Shah M. Development Milestones. [Updated 2023 Mar 16]. In: St